==Housing==
Brooklyn offers a wide array of private housing, as well as public housing, which is administered by the New York City Housing Authority (NYCHA). Affordable rental and co-operative housing units throughout the borough were created under the Mitchell–Lama Housing Program.<ref>[https://www.nyc.gov/site/hpd/services-and-information/mitchell-lama-program.page Mitchell-Lama] date=January 5, 2024 , New York City Department of Housing Preservation and Development. Accessed January 5, 2024.
ER  - 

TY  - GEN
TI  - He also went after property owners who had not paid back taxes. This increase in city revenue enabled him to reduce the city's debt and increase services. However, raising taxes proved extremely unpopular.

=====Mayors of the City of Brooklyn=====
Borough President#Brooklyn Borough Presidents
Brooklyn elected a mayor from 1834 until 1898, after which it was consolidated into the City of Greater New York, the second mayor of which (1902–1903), Seth Low, had been Mayor of Brooklyn from 1882 to 1885. Since 1898, Brooklyn has, in place of a separate mayor, elected a Borough President.
